[1] North Carolina: donkey
Date: Tue 17 Aug 2021
Source: Southern Farm Network Today [edited]
http://sfntoday.com/nc-commissioner-troxler-nc-sees-first-cases-of-eee-and-west-nile-virus/


The state has recently seen its 1st cases of triple E (eastern equine encephalomyelitis) and West Nile virus (WNV). Both of these can be fatal in equines and both can be prevented with vaccinations. Confirming these 2 cases is a reminder for equine owners to vaccinate their animals.

The West Nile case was in an unvaccinated donkey in Guilford County and the triple E case was in an unvaccinated horse in Pender County [for more information on the EEE case, please see ProMED-mail eastern equine encephalitis postings. - Mod.TG]

Both of these mosquito-borne diseases can be fatal in equine, but both are also preventable through vaccinations. These positive cases serve as a great reminder horse and donkey owners should have their animals vaccinated.

It is not unusual to see these diseases in the state, but I am glad we are just seeing the 1st cases now. Overall, we did have 9 cases in 2020 with the 1st one coming in July [2021].

It is not "news" to anyone living in North Carolina, mosquitoes are prevalent until 1st frost, which can be as late as November. Rainfall from tropical storms in late summer can help set up a perfect breeding environment for mosquitoes, but it doesn't take a lot of water to create an environment for these pests.

Even puddles from brief summer storms can create a perfect breeding ground if they stick around for 4 days or longer. Any measures you can take around the barn or fields to reduce standing water is great for lessening the opportunity for mosquitoes to multiply.

Dump containers [old tires, the catch pot on potted plants, etc. - Mod.TG] and removing water from puddles are 2 simple steps to take. Other tips include keeping horses in stalls at night, using insect screens [and sprays especially approved for horses. - Mod.TG] and fans, and turning off lights after dusk. Watch your animals closely for signs your animals are sick.

Signs of West Nile Virus are fever, weakness or paralysis of hind limbs, impaired vision, head pressing, seizures, and aimless wandering. Contact your vet immediately if you notice your equine exhibiting any of these signs.

People, horses, and birds can become infected by a bite from a mosquito carrying these diseases, but there is no evidence horses can transmit the viruses to other horses, birds or people through direct contact. People invest a lot in their equine and vaccination is the best way to keep them safe from these mosquito-borne diseases.

