[3] Colorado: horses
Date: Fri 3 Sep 2021
Source: Greeley Tribune [edited]
https://www.greeleytribune.com/2021/09/02/state-veterinarian-confirms-more-equine-west-nile-virus-cases-in-weld-county/


Four more horses in Weld County have tested positive for equine West Nile virus, raising the statewide total to 14 since late July [2021], according to the Colorado Department of Agriculture.

In addition to the horses in Weld, 3 horses in Adams County, 2 in Boulder County, and one each in Elbert, Otero, Morgan, and Fremont have tested positive for West Nile virus. The 1st case of equine West Nile was identified in Colorado on [30 Jul 2021].

"With more than a dozen horses testing positive for West Nile Virus this year [2021], it's important to remember that vaccinations are critical to protect the health of Colorado horses," state veterinarian Dr Maggie Baldwin said in the news release. "In addition to vaccines, horse owners should work to reduce mosquito populations on their premises. West Nile virus is spread by mosquitoes and mitigating that vector helps to reduce the risk of disease to both horses and people."

West Nile virus is a disease that cycles between wild birds and mosquitoes, and can sometimes affect other species, like people and horses. Clinical cases in horses are typically characterized by anorexia, depression and neurological signs that might include ataxia, weakness, or paralysis of one or more limbs, teeth grinding, aimless wandering, convulsions, and circling.

Mosquito pools from Weld, Larimer, Boulder, Adams, Arapahoe, Delta, Denver, and Pueblo counties have tested positive for the virus this summer [2021], and the Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment [CDPHE] has recorded 29 human cases of the virus this year. Weld County reported at least one woman was hospitalized last month [August 2021] with the virus, and another was diagnosed.

CDPHE publishes data on human West Nile cases and positive mosquito pools on the health department website.

Vaccination for West Nile virus is one of the core vaccines recommended for livestock by the American Association of Equine Practitioners [AAEP]. If a horse has not been vaccinated in previous years, it will need the 2-shot vaccination series. Horses need an annual booster to protect against the virus. The state agriculture department suggests visiting the AAEP website for a comprehensive list of vaccination recommendations.

Horse owners should work with their veterinarians to determine the best vaccine schedule for their horses.

In addition to vaccinations, horse owners should also work diligently to reduce mosquito populations and their possible breeding areas where horses are located. Recommendations include removing stagnant water sources, using mosquito repellents and keeping animals inside during the bugs' feeding times, typically early in the morning and evening.

If a horse displays clinical signs consistent with neurologic disease, a complete veterinary examination is warranted. All infectious or contagious equine neurologic diseases are reportable to the Colorado State Veterinarian's Office.

[Byline: Anne Delaney]

